Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{In humans, places or contexts previously associated with alcohol use
   often provoke relapse during abstinence. This phenomenon is modeled in
   laboratory animals using the ABA renewal procedure, in which extinction
   training in context (B) suppresses alcohol seeking, and renewal of this
   seeking occurs when the animal returns to the original training context
   (A). However, extinction training does not adequately capture the
   motivation for abstinence in human alcoholics who typically
   self-initiate abstinence in response to the negative consequences of
   excessive use. We recently developed a procedure to study renewal in
   laboratory rats after abstinence imposed by negative consequences
   (footshock punishment). The mechanisms of renewal of punished alcohol
   seeking are largely unknown. Here, we used the D1-family receptor
   antagonist SCH 23390 to examine the role of nucleus accumbens (NAc)
   shell and core dopamine in renewal of alcohol seeking after
   punishment-imposed abstinence. We trained alcohol-preferring ``P
   rats{''} to self-administer 20\% alcohol in Context A and subsequently
   suppressed alcohol taking via response-contingent footshock punishment
   in Context B. We tested the effects of systemic, NAc shell, or NAc core
   injections of SCH 23390 on renewal of alcohol seeking after
   punishment-imposed abstinence. We found that both systemic and NAc shell
   and core injections of SCH 23390 decreased renewal of punished alcohol
   seeking. Our results demonstrate a critical role of NAc dopamine in
   renewal of alcohol seeking after punishment-imposed abstinence. We
   discuss these results in reference to the brain mechanisms of renewal of
   alcohol seeking after extinction versus punishment.}},
