Year = {{2014}},
Volume = {{9}},
Number = {{6}},
Pages = {{737-750}},
Month = {{JUN}},
Abstract = {{In the current functional MRI study, we investigated interactions
   between reward and threat processing. Visual cues at the start of each
   trial informed participants about the chance of winning monetary reward
   and/or receiving a mild aversive shock. We tested two competing
   hypothesis: according to the `salience hypothesis', in the condition
   involving both reward and threat, enhanced activation would be observed
   because of increased salience; according to the `competition
   hypothesis', the processing of reward and threat would trade-off against
   each other, leading to reduced activation. Analysis of skin conductance
   data during a delay phase revealed an interaction between reward and
   threat processing, such that the effect of reward was reduced during
   threat and the effect of threat was reduced during reward. Analysis of
   imaging data during the same task phase revealed interactions between
   reward and threat processing in several regions, including the
   midbrain/ventral tegmental area, caudate, putamen, bed nucleus of the
   stria terminalis, anterior insula, middle frontal gyrus and dorsal
   anterior cingulate cortex. Taken together, our findings reveal
   conditions during which reward and threat trade-off against each other
   across multiple sites. Such interactions are suggestive of competitive
   processes and may reflect the organization of opponent systems in the
   brain.}},
