Abstract = {{Here we present a novel approach to quickly and reliably find long (200
   ms 2 s) stereotyped sequences of sounds ({''}motifs{''}) in acoustic
   recordings of birdsong. Robust and time-efficient identification of such
   sequences is a crucial first step in many studies ranging from
   development to neuronal basis of motor behavior. Accurately identifying
   motifs is usually hindered by the presence of animal-intrinsic
   variability in execution and tempo, and by extrinsic acoustic noise (e.
   g., movement artifacts, ambient noise). The algorithm we describe in
   this report has been optimized to work in bird species that sing
   stereotyped syllable sequences (such as the zebra finch), and requires
   minimal user involvement (similar to 5 min for over 1,000 motifs).
